While thousands of whole-genome sequences are now available and easily accessible for close to real-time visualization in platforms such as NexStrain on the GISAID database (GISAID; 
 https://www.epicov.org) (Elbe and Buckland-Merrett, 2017; Shu and McCauley, 2017), there has been a significant shortage on genomic information from SA ever since the virus first arrived in Brazil in March 2019. By 12 June 2020, entries from Brazil, Chile, Ecuador, Colombia, Uruguay, Peru, and Argentina have been deposited corresponding to 373 genomes available for this region [
 15]. However, there are no studies addressing genomic diversity and how this may impact molecular diagnosis of SARS-CoV-2. Thus, herein we compared the capacity of all currently accessible primer-probe sets to detect potential SARS-CoV-2 variants by analyzing against all available South American genomes while also assessing regional variation and how this may perhaps predict test performance by screening for potential mutations affecting regions harboring primer-probe binding sites.
